      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re Steven R. Weisman's Sept. 29 Editorial Observer, ''The Senator and the Talmud: A Case Study'': As an observant Jew, I was chilled by the prediction that if Joseph I. Lieberman is elected vice president, his ''conduct could lead to a significant evolution in Jewish law and history.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re Steven R. Weisman's Sept. 29 Editorial Observer, ''The Senator and the Talmud: A Case Study'': As an observant Jew, I was chilled by the prediction that if Joseph I. Lieberman is elected vice president, his ''conduct could lead to a significant evolution in Jewish law and history.''</p>
        <p>A century ago, observant Jews on the doorstep of America were pressured to abandon their strict adherence to religious doctrine. After all, they were told, nobody keeps the Sabbath in America; stop clinging to the Old World. Fortunately, many Jews persevered, and today I can wear a yarmulke to work and my unavailability on Friday night and Saturday is never challenged.</p>
        <p>Despite whatever specific exceptions Mr. Lieberman might use personally because of his unique position, observant Jews will continue to keep the Sabbath in the traditional manner.</p>
        <p>RICHARD S. SEVRINSKY  Brooklyn, Sept. 29, 2000</p>
      </block>
